President Joe Biden has announced his intention to appoint Maria-Elena Giner as the U.S. Commissioner of the International Boundary and Water Commission. If confirmed, Giner would be the first Latina to hold this position. The International Boundary and Water Commission is responsible for implementing boundary and water treaties between the United States and Mexico, as well as addressing issues related to rivers, sanitation, water quality, and flood control in the border region. Giner has over 25 years of experience working on water issues in the U.S.-Mexico border region and previously served as the General Manager for the Border Environment Cooperation Commission. She has led the development and financing of $9 billion in environmental infrastructure projects, benefiting numerous communities and millions of residents. Giner holds a Bachelor of Science in Civil Engineering, a Master of Business Administration, and a Ph.D. in Public Policy. She is also a registered professional engineer in the state of Texas.